HESA Policy Explorer — Streamlit App
=====================================

Launch
------
    export OLLAMA_HOST=http://100.85.195.54:11434
    uv run --no-sync streamlit run app/streamlit_app.py

The `--no-sync` flag is required on this Mac. See "torch wheel issue" below.


Tabs
----
1. Classify       — Select a CMA section or paste text; keyword rules vs gemma4:12b
2. Ask the record — RAG Q&A over the HESA corpus with source-type filtering
3. Evaluation     — Pre-computed classifier results table + confusion matrix
4. Gap analysis   — CMA sections cross-referenced against briefs/reports/responses


Prerequisites
-------------
Before launching the app, build the ChromaDB index if not already present:

    uv run --no-sync python -m rag.build_index

To populate the Gap Analysis tab, run the precompute script (takes ~10 min):

    export OLLAMA_HOST=http://100.85.195.54:11434
    uv run --no-sync python scripts/precompute_gap.py

Then open results/gap_analysis.json and fill in each "status" field by hand:
valid values are: echoed / endorsed / committed / unaddressed


Offline fallback
----------------
If OLLAMA_HOST is not set or the remote server is unreachable:
- Tab 1 (Classify): shows a cached gemma4 prediction from demo/cached_classify.json
- Tab 2 (Ask): shows a cached answer + passages from demo/cached_ask.json
- Tabs 3 and 4 load from disk only and always work offline


torch wheel issue (macOS 15 x86_64)
-------------------------------------
This project pins torch==2.11.0 in pyproject.toml for compatibility with the
Linux GPU server (RTX 3060, CUDA). That version has no wheel for
macosx_15_0_x86_64 (the 2018 MacBook running macOS 15 on Intel).

Running `uv sync` on this Mac fails with:
    Distribution `torch==2.11.0` can't be installed because it doesn't have a
    source distribution or wheel for the current platform

Workaround: use `uv run --no-sync` for all commands on this Mac. This skips
the sync step and runs with whatever packages are already installed in .venv.

The app does not import torch directly. sentence-transformers (used by
ChromaDB's SentenceTransformerEmbeddingFunction) imports torch internally, but
the installed version in .venv is compatible with this machine's CPU — only
the pinned 2.11.0 wheel is missing, not torch itself.

Do NOT run `uv sync` on this Mac — it will fail. The .venv is managed from
the Linux server where the pinned torch wheel is available.
